This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) category as it deals with hyperspectral data analysis, which is a common task in computer vision. Additionally, the use of graph Laplacian and lasso penalty are common techniques in computer vision. 

The paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category as it proposes a new method for hyperspectral unmixing using Nonnegative Matrix Factorization (NMF), which is a popular machine learning technique. 

The Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) category is also a possibility as the paper proposes a new method for data analysis, which is a common task in artificial intelligence. 

The Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) category is another possibility as NMF is a popular technique in neural networks and the paper proposes a new method for NMF. 

Finally, the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category is a possibility as the paper proposes a new structured sparse constraint, which is a common topic in data structures and algorithms.
